Metcash launches grassroots campaign against Aldi's intrusion into the industry
Metcash is trying to protect his IGA deal from Aldi's attack in South and Western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a grassroots campaign to defend IGA traders' market share in South and Western Australia ahead of Aldi's 700 million dollar attack.
Aldi is preparing to open two distribution centers and the first store early next year in South and Western Australia, where up to 120 stores are coming. At the same time, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food brokers and building the IGA brand through mainstream and social media marketing, as well as through events such as the Adelaide show.
IGA traders and suppliers have jumped in, and brands like the ice cream maker Simmo’s from Dunsborough offer a taste of the IGA’s stores, and store owners sell discounted tickets to Australian football matches for their regular customers.
Metcash is expected to reveal more details about its defense strategy on September 29, when this food, alcohol and hardware wholesaler will hold an annual Investor Strategy Day.
There is a lot in the game, as South and Western Australia together account for almost 30 percent of the territory of Metcash IGA stores, where the yield margins are higher than those of the IGA network in the eastern states of Metcash.
For South and Western Australia, shoppers are known to be parochial, and IGA dealers have a much higher market share than New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland: more than 30% in the south and 24 percent in the West compared to 14 percent in the Eastern States.
However, analysts like Morgan Stanley believe that Aldi will grab about 5 percent of the food market in the two states within 12 months of opening the first moves. Turnover is obtained from all operators, but mainly from independent retailers.
In this week's report, Morgan Stanley analyst Tom Kierath estimates that IGA dealers could lose US$360 million in sales each year and Metcash could lose US$250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that next year Aldi will open 25 stores in the south and 30 in the West, generating a turnover of 500 and 600 million dollars in these areas.
Loss of food and food sales and volumes at Metcash's high fixed cost base could cost Metcash about 13 million dollars in operating profit losses before interest and taxes, Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market share in the eastern states, mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent Roy Morgan study found that IGA's customers were the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley believes that Metcash's food and food sales will fall by 3.8% in 2016; 4.1 percent in 2017 and 2.1 percent in 2018, with its market share dropping from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3% in 2020.
Last week, Hamish Douglass, the head of the Lead Investment Fund and founder of the Magella Financial Group, said at a business lunch in Melbourne that Metcash could “well possibly lose in a decade.”
Metcash has publicly declined to respond to Douglass' comments.
However, it is understood that a member of the board of Metcash had contacted Douglass last week.
Since 2010, IGA's market share has declined from 18% to 14 percent, and revenues from Metcash's food and food business, which supplies products to approximately 1200 IGA dealers, have declined by 43 percent since 2012. This indicates a reduction in the debt financing of operations when sales and margins are under pressure.
However, the wholesaler holds its own, and has invested more than US$150 million each year, lowering the prices of hundreds of products to the same level as Coles and Woolworths, helping IGA retailers refurbish stores by increasing the faster-growing fresh food, and launching a better range of private brand products.
