The researchers said the worms show the functionality of a new method, named audio genetics. In it, ultrasound can be used to activate certain brain, heart and muscle cells from outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told The Guardian that the method could one day replace deep brain stimulation. It is an invasive procedure in which electrical impulses are led to the human brain to treat Parkinson's disease.
The nematodes do not normally react to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that when they were surrounded by a liquid with microscopic bubbles, the situation changed.
He noticed that the bubbles reinforced ultrasound waves, which then pass inside the worms.
Reinforced ultrasonic waves affect the TRP-4 ion channels, the structures that are present in the cell membranes of some worms.
Sound waves make these ion channels open and activate the cells attached to them, according to a report published in the journal Nature Communications.
To manufacture ultrasound-controlled nematodes, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motion neurons have TRP-4 ion channels.
When Chalasani used ultrasound on modified worms, microbubbles reinforced sound waves and transmitted them to worms where they turn on the modified motion neurons.
The method has some of the same features as optogenetics, a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn on and off nerve cells using light pulses.
However, Chalasani says that the use of sonogenetics may have some advantages over optogenetics.
Unlike the light that needs to be sent along the optical fiber to the desired spot inside the brain, low-frequency ultrasonic waves can pass through the tissue unhindered, so they can be sent to the brain from the top of the skull.
“We believe that using gene therapy and the therapeutic virus may make it possible to temporarily cause the affected human nerve cells to react to ultrasound signals in certain neurological treatments in a clinical environment,” Chalasani said.
Other applications could focus on muscle cells and insulin-producing cells, he added.
