Psychologist advises: How to tell children about refugees
In recent days, many parents have had to think about how to tell the child about the situation of refugees seeking to reach Europe.
Or is it worth telling at all?
There is no need to bring it up by force, advises Ferdinand Garoff, a member of the SPR's crisis team.
It is worth protecting smaller children, and not, for example, let them watch the news alone.
Young children are not always able to understand what they are seeing, and it can be remembered and distressed, he says.
However, if a child has come across news photos of refugees on television or heard about it elsewhere, it is worth bringing it up.
It is a good idea to have a conversation on the child's starting point and listen carefully to what he or she is asking.
The fears of the child may be surprising.
They are not necessarily the ones that a parent thinks he is afraid of.
It is not worth scaring the child in vain, even if you are anxious and afraid of yourself.
A smaller child closely monitors the behavior of their parents.
If the parents themselves remain calm during the conversation, the child will feel safe.
Older children are likely to come across a conversation about refugees at school, with friends or online.
It is a good idea for parents to bring up the matter with them if the matter concerns the child.
The fact is that not all people in the world are doing well.
Parents can think together with the children about how we feel about this in our family.
In the end, do we think the world is a safe or unsafe place?
Parents may also have different educational perspectives - some may want to protect their children from anxiety if possible.
On the other hand: If the family also talks about difficult issues, the child will get a model of how to deal with the difficulties that come up in life.
This could be useful to him in the future.
