This week, U.S. central bank decision-makers are sitting around a huge mahogany table for a long-awaited meeting to decide whether the time has come to raise the policy rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
At the other end of the central bank's decorative, two-storey meeting room is a mural from the United States.
The map is a reminder that the chairman of the central bank, Janet L. Yellen and his colleagues should put the economic interests of the nation above everything else.
Congress has put two of the central bank's shoulders: they need to maximize U.S. employment and keep prices stable.
However, since the Great Deal of Recession, the central bank's leaders have accepted that there is also a third, unwritten mandate: economic stability.
It is precisely this third requirement that could be a decisive factor in the decision to be published on Thursday, which is so strict that it cannot even be predicted. A decision on whether the U.S. economy is ready to be weaned from a record incentive that the short-term interest rate that has remained at almost zero since late 2008 has brought .
While the majority of the data show a steady increase in the economy, the recent turmoil in the global financial markets may have made bank officials on alert in advance even more frightened when it comes to increasing instability. It is feared how it would be if the federal funds rate were increased by even a percentage point quarter.
“Understandably, the labour market and inflation are the first and most important issues to be monitored,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economic expert at the brokerage company Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“However, I believe that if they seek the justification for rescheduling interest rates, the increased uncertainty in the world market is a valid enough reason to wait,” he said.
No agreement has been reached on the central bank's decision, which also creates nervousness in the economy.
According to a recent Bloomberg survey, about half of economic experts predict that interest rates will rise this week.
The financial markets, on the other hand, expect the central bank to delay the drawdown, as according to the key indicator, the opportunity to grow is only about 30 per cent.
This indicates a decline in the securities markets if the central bank raises the level, unless the decision-makers then manage to soften the blow by promising that the next increase will not take place in the near future.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average index rose 228.89 points, or 1.4 percent, with a new figure of 16 599.85.
The recovery was brought with it by the expectation that the central bank will keep the level unchanged this week, according to John Lonski, the main economic expert of the Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
“It’s surprising if the central bank raises interest rates right now,” he says.
If policymakers raise interest rates, “they have to put a lot of effort into their policy to support the financial markets so that they don’t panic.”
Other experts argue that the increased level would calm the financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the central bank will operate.
Just a month ago, it seemed that the central bank would be raising interest rates this month by a quarter of a percentage point, thus taking the first small step towards a slow tightening of the monetary situation, which would ensure the stability of the US recovery.
Yellen has stated in the spring and early summer that he expects the level to rise this year despite the fact that liberals are calling for more economic development in their complaints.
Although the creation of new jobs slowed down in August, labour market growth has been stable this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1 per cent last month, the lowest figure in seven years and close to the level that the central bank considers to be the limit for full employment.
The increase in wages has shown signs of a pick-up.
Although inflation is still below the central bank's annual target of 2%, according to the central bank's decision-makers, the main reason for this is the temporary impact of the significantly lower oil price.
The economy “can survive higher interest rates and also need them, given the tight situation in the labour market,” says Ian Shepherdson, chief economic expert at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world were shaken last week when China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average index fell as much as 16 percent from its May record, with investors fearing that China would slow the economy slow down global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, and the Dow index is now nearly 10 percent below the peak in May.
For central bank decision-makers, the turmoil in the market is an additional factor in the complex equation, which indicates when interest rates should be raised.
“Without these financial market events and the news of the weakness of the Chinese economy in recent weeks, policymakers would tighten the level at this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, Senior Researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former central bank official.
Now he predicts that decision-makers will wait at least a month to get a better idea of the effects.
“The potential impact on the U.S. economy is still rather unclear, and they have little information at their disposal regarding the consequences of China’s events,” Oliner said.
The well-being of the international economy is not the main concern of the central bank, so in principle it should not influence decision-making.
In practice, however, the Federal Central Bank has become the world's monetary authority.
In recent years, the central bank's influence has been immense.
In 2013, then chairman, Ben S. Bernanken, a hint that the central bank can “narrow” the increase in the amount of money caused upheavals in the markets around the world.
In a world where the market and economies are increasingly weaved, central bank officials are expected not only to follow the development elsewhere, but also to consult other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
The central bank’s decision-making process is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at asset management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Virginia, this month, pointed out that “the central bank has previously overreacted to a financial market movement that has appeared to be separate from the fundamentals of the economy.”
The decision-making Federal Open Market Committee has called for an increase in interest rates, and Lacker, a member of the committee's right to vote, as an example, appeals to the 1998-99 decisions.
The Asian economic crisis caused the central bank to cut its benchmark by 0.75 percentage points over three meetings “despite its limited, recognizable impact on U.S. economic growth,” Lacker said.
A year later, the central bank overturned these cuts.
The central bank should put economic stability first only during a major crisis, as the market collapsed in 2008, says Adam S. Pose, former member of the Bank of England Interest Rate Determination Committee.
The latest turmoil does not come anywhere near its level, Posen says.
“No one wants to be in a situation where there is a fear of raising interest rates because the market is upset,” said Posen, chairman of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still includes a two-way requirement and does not mention financial stability. As long as this is the case, I do not think they should anticipate it.
