“It takes a long time to get mortality data,” said Dr. Robin Blackstone. He is a weight loss surgery expert who wrote an editorial for a new study in the journal JAMA Surgery.
In weight loss or bariatric surgery, different methods are used to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the absorption of food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been found to be effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but the majority of the subjects in the study have been morbidly obese, and their body mass index (BMI) has been 35 or more.
The BMI, or weight ratio to height, is considered normal when it is between 18.5 and 24.9.
If the BMI is over 25, it indicates that someone is overweight, and if a person's BMI is more than 30, they are considered to be obese.
You can calculate your own BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For this new study, researchers at the Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery, gastric bypass surgery, and gastric reduction, for the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people who were mildly obese.
The study showed that the average BMI of the cuts decreased from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year.
At the same time, the BMI of people treated by means other than surgery remained roughly the same in 29.
Of the people undergoing surgery, 36% had diabetes completely and 28% partially.
For comparison, in the medically treated group, diabetes was completely cured by only 1 percent and partly by about 2%.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides and the “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgery group,” the authors noted.
The researchers also monitored patients' blood hemoglobin A1c levels, which reflect blood sugar levels in the long term.
Hemoglobin A1c should remain below 7 percent, the researchers wrote.
The post-operative hemoglobin A1c level dropped from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
However, in the medical treatment group, it remained stable at around 8 per cent.
However, this better ‘glycemic control’ described by improved haemoglobin A1c levels did not reduce mortality over a five-year period, said lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and his colleagues.
The research group also compared the average results between two different types of surgery.
At the fifth year, when compared with the group that underwent gastric reduction surgery, the gastric bypass group had lost more weight (18.7 and 14.2 kg), lowered their body mass index (7.4 and 5.1), lowered their haemoglobin A1c levels (3.1 percent and 2.1 percent), and was more likely to have achieved complete diabetes remission (46.9% and 16.7%).
The University of Arizona College of Medicine-Phoenixin Blackstone says that while the study does not show survival or surgery after five years, there are research results from Sweden where the surgery led to a longer life in heavier people.
A Swedish study found that obese people who had undergone weight loss surgery had a 29 percent lower chance of dying over a 15-year period when compared to a group that had tried more traditional treatments.
Although the new study does not show an improvement in the survival of surgical patients, Blackstone says the results are nevertheless encouraging for people with a BMI below 35 who are interested in the surgery.
“The research results are crucial precisely because they show that the surgery is safe for the lower body mass index group,” he said.
Blackstone adds that both patients and their doctors should take the weight very seriously when the patient's BMI is between 27 and 30.
“I think we’re waiting too long before we take this seriously,” he said.
I believe that when a person has accumulated these genetic changes that permanently prepare their body for obesity and diabetes, it is very difficult to reverse the situation.
