Our digital lives have doubled the need to appear strong, cheerful and successful, when in reality isolation dominates.
This superficial success is dominated by the values that psychologists call external: money, image, social status. All this is done at the expense of the inner values - the personal growth and friendship of the inner longing - that will have a deeper impact on our mental health.
And as the billionaire video game developer recently explained, money really doesn't get greater happiness.
The beauty of the Friends was that it turned this focus on its head.
No character defined their work, but rather their personality, which was clearly distinguished by interaction as friends.
Joey and Chandler's numerous hugs, moments in comfortable chairs, watching football, Ross longing for Rachel - the humor of these came from the knowledge that yes, men can relate to all this, although they often hesitate to fully explore their feelings.
As a volunteer at Samaritans explained to me: “When I listen to people who are depressed and suicidal, I have truly understood how even the slightest interaction with a friend can make you feel better.”
Often, men who contact us feel that they cannot talk to friends.
The old idea of “getting over” is strong, as is the feeling that if you open up about problems, you see weakness.
Friends is one of those series that comes to mind when I try to offer more long-term means of survival.
It emphasized the small moments of friendship between men.
Although my impartial, external position on the other end of the phone helps people with moments of despair, long-term support comes from a close, personal network of family and friends.
And so if you're taking part in the FriendsFest at Comedy Central this weekend, and all the locations have been redesigned to celebrate the occasion, why don't you take your friends for coffee in Central Perk.
Or, even better, if you see someone lonely at Starbucks, smile and say hello.
You never know how much your friendship can mean.
