Xi urges to open the economy to the wider world
The economy needs to open up more to the outside world to promote growth, President Xi Jinping told a group on Tuesday to guide the reform.
“China should commit to attracting foreign funding and expertise and developing a policy of transparency,” he said, addressing the 16th meeting of the leading group on the deepening of the general reform.
Supporting transparency while driving reforms further new movement and vitality, and creating new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The Management Team adopted a series of guidelines, including a negative list of market access, a laxisation of border control principles, the call for state-owned enterprises to take up private capital, and a review of the resident registration system.
According to the opinion, a negative list is created to name the sectors and companies that are not allowed to be invested in.
The system is gradually being tested and improved through pilot programmes.
The change is significant, as it will give the market a greater role in the allocation of resources, ensure a legal business environment and make the market more transparent, the statement said.
The government also loosens its control over the power it distributes to companies, thus ensuring that companies decide for themselves how to manage their business.
The statement also said that China will allow border regions to explore new cross-border economic cooperation models and new mechanisms for the development of regional growth.
In order to open state-controlled sectors, more sectors will be opened up to private financiers.
“The government will not change its policy on foreign investment, and it will protect the legal interests of foreign-funded companies and provide them with better services,” the statement said.
In addition, the application process for permanent residents of foreigners, ‘green cards’, will be facilitated by optimising the requirements and streamlining the application process.
The meeting also discussed the guarantee of the professional rights of lawyers and the support of professional judges and prosecutors.
The meeting was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang, as well as senior leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, said in a statement released after the meeting.
